text: quentin is my second favorite director of all time. he was flawless and electrifying up until django which wasn't bad but wasn't exactly genius like he always is... hateful 8 was horrible and i'm very worried based on this trailer... this seems to be following in the tradition of his last 4 films of being terribly depicted period pieces. all his films have had a gorgeous visual style but for some reason inglourious basterds had a bit of a lull in the aesthetic, he shot it in 1 year, but the writing was so insanely genius it didn't even matter that there were almost no moving shots in the whole film or if some of the costume/makeup/art direction could have been better.... django and hateful eight just had terrible costume design and art direction.... quentin, this does not look like a great depiction of the 60's and 70's visually because you're not going for an overly authentic look... the costumes in your last 4 films don't look like they were ever worn by the characters a day before the actor got on set. tarantino has done so much for film and is a cinematic genius and god forever but that whole "carry his load" joke was lame and brad pitt's acting looks 10 times worse than in inglourious basterds. he has to be the second worst actor in the QT universe after QT. anyway, i've said my 2 cents. I HOPE I'M WRONG. BRING ON ANOTHER MASTERPIECE!!! Inglourious Basterds was too long ago!!! One of the greatest films of all time!!!!  that guy looks nothing like charles manson... is that supposed to be him? the black and white at the begining looks digital.. shoudl have gone for an older / granier film stock.

text: Man! NO PRESSURE...but it's almost SCARY... to think what Quentin Tarantino's 10th film is going to be like!?!  This TRAILER could sell tickets! LOL  DiCaprio. Pitt. Robbie, PACINO, OLYPHANT, Damian Lewis, Kurt "F@#CkinG" Russell (Best Wyatt Earp Ever!...sorry Jimmy RIP),Tim Roth, Marsden and pretty much EVERY A-List Actors in Hollywood along with the single best Bruce Lee impression I have ever seen!   But I guess that shouldn't be too surprising given Quentin Tarantino's love for martial arts movies. (OH!!! THAT'S HIS NEXT FILM!!! and should have Jackie Chan, Jet Li and all great living martial arts masters!    Done by Quentin Tarantino!?!    (Thinking... I'm wondering if Hollywood made a deal with Quentin Tarantino to hire half of Hollywood and release this film mid-summer to give the other "blockbuster" summer movies a chance to get some revenue before this one hits theaters?   Because once it does only a handful of films will likely even register at the Box Office.)  They'd have to pass out anti-stroke medication at the ticket counter because of the intense back to back, visceral action and fight scenes... I digress...)  Quentin Tarantino is probably the only person in Hollywood to get most of these actors willing to do one of his projects for "scale) but I'm sure the CAA and WME people wouldn't allow that!  My only complaint is I think "The Quentin" needs to start selling stock in each movie project so us mere mortal members of the public can get a piece of the financial action. Heck! He might never need to go to Hollywood for another dime ever again! (do they still make dimes?)  Another Tarantino "Cult Classic" gone mainstream!   Congrats QT!

text: ourforgiveness. c*o*m  Have you ever asked yourself why read the Bible (the Word of God); imagine a sky scrapper that has 200 floors, you step into the elevator and as you begin your ascension you first see at eye level, and as you rise, by the time you reach the 50th floor, you are able to receive a greater view of the city, and by the time you have reached the 100th floor, your panorama view is amazing; roads, houses, and people are everywhere. And finally, once you reach the top, your reaction is breathtaking as you are able to see for miles. What changed? I mean technically, you were in the same spot, but you just had a different point of view as the elevation increased. Well, in Like so manner, reading and studying the bible thru the Spirit of God (Holy Spirit) will amplify your understanding and knowledge of every word that is written. As a newly converted Christian, you may at first begin to see the superficial of the text, but as you mature in spirit, you begin to discover new angles, meanings, revelations, connections, or understandings of the very same verse. And at times the revelation can be so profound that you simply sit back and ponder on the depths of each and every word. After all, every word was carefully selected by God. I tell you, time begins to accelerate and light shortens when you seek after the many fold mysteries of God. He who has saith that the bible is dull or boring, has not know his maker. He who has made claim to have read the bible in a short period of time, has not diligently searched for the hidden angles. For I tell you, and many brothers would attest, that it takes a lifetime to learn to live by the Word of God. If any man seeks after knowledge, wisdom, and understanding, but above all, a relationship with God, then this is a call for you.   How be it that the world is not rushing to inquire of such great power and truth? -Its free to everyone.

text: I don't know. It's interesting. But I'm lukewarm on the tone, here. This is just a teaser, so who knows. I'm just hoping Tarantino plays the Tate-murders more "straight" than...not. Hard to gauge from this footage. Basically my hope is the tone of this film is more similar to Jules Winnfield's monologue at the end of "Pulp Fiction" ("YOU'RE the weak, and I am the tyranny of evil men. But I'm trying, Ringo- I'm trying REAL HARD...to be the shepard"), as opposed to the sort of almost whimsical, quasi-lighter touch (in my opinion) he's displayed recently (such as the operatic carnage and dancing horse at the end of "Django Unchained").   And I'm hoping he doesn't go too overboard with the anachronisms. But if he DOES....I hope he goes overboard well. I'll never not root for him. He's one of our great living filmmakers, and so I can't wait to see this, and judge it on its own terms.

text: Shut up, and take my money

Whatever movie he makes after this is his last. Too bad, I really love every movie he's made. I saw The Hateful Eight at a special widescreen edition premiere with my best friends. We stood in line for +3 hours in15-degree weather. When we finally got in we were all kind of miserable and regretting spending $20 each on tickets because our hands and feet were numb. We sat down for the movie. The owner of the theatre came out and starting talking about the filming techniques used for the movie. Then Quentin Tarantino came out wearing mittens,  an aviator hat, and a brown leather jacket. He talked about how hard it was to make that movie and that he wanted to make one in this format since he was a little kid watching spaghetti westerns, he said the f word probably 100 times within the 3 minutes he talked. He was so hyper and passionate he couldn't contain himself, it was like he was more excited to watch his movie than we were just because it was made in a special widescreen format only perfectly suited for a few theatres including this one. That was one of my favorite days. Mr. Tarantino is a true artist.

text: I like how I have no idea what the movie is about but I'm pretty much sold anyway. More trailers should be like this. Just show off the talent and give a taste of the atmosphere and aesthetic without giving away the plot, so we can enjoy the storytelling of the film as the filmmakers intended. In this case we don't even know the premise and that's all the better. We're going to see it anyway as long as the reviews aren't terrible, and probably even if they are, because it's Tarantino and big stars with big skills and the setting is right up his alley. So let's go this movie and be surprised at the inevitable twists and turns. Perhaps it will even defy our expectations.

Whilst hateful eight was good it‚Äôs not one of Tarantino‚Äôs best films.   Pitt hasn't been in anything great for a while, not since the big short anyway.  Whilst Leo has been busy saving the environment and hasn't been on screen since the revenant.  It's luke perry's and burt reynold's last ever film.  Al pacino is part of the cast and again when was the last time he was in something cool?   It's like a career revival for it's principal cast.  Think Michael Keaton with bird man or John Travolta for pulp fiction. In fact i'm getting a very strong pulp fiction vibe from this. text: Dear Recipient¬†  We kindly request you to spend a few moments of your time reading this letter because it just might be possible that this letter will open before you a new dimension of your role as a human being in this universe. We hope that you are a free thinking, broadminded, and prejudice-free human being whose goal is to find the truth. Before we continue, let us state to you the purpose of this letter- that this is an introduction and invitation to the way of life known as Islam.    SOME FACTS    Islam has approximately 1 billion followers known as Muslims who follow the final revelation to mankind, known as the "Qur'an", revealed to Prophet Muhammad about 1400 years ago. Contrary to the common misconception, only about 20% of all Muslims are Arabs, the rest are Indians, Indonesians, Bosnians,Africans,Chinese,turkish and so on .¬†   WHAT IS ISLAM    Islam, unlike most other religions, is not named after any man. Instead Islam means the submission of one's will to the only true god worthy of worship "Allah" and anyone who does so is termed a "Muslim". The word also implies "peace" which is the natural consequence of total submission to the will of Allah. Islam is the religion that was given to Adam, the first man and the first prophet of Allah, and it was the religion of all the prophets sent by Allah to mankind like Jesus and Moses .¬†   THE MESSAGE OF ISLAM    The most important message of Islam is the absolute Unity of God-that there is only One Supreme Being who has no partners and is not dependent on anyone or anything. He is the creator of everything and the whole universe is under His control. Since the total submission of one's will to Allah represents the essence of worship, Islam is the worship of Allah alone and the avoidance of worship directed to any person, place or thing other than Allah. In essence, Islam calls man away from the worship of creation and invites him to worship only its Creator. Allah is the only one deserving man's worship as it is only by His will that prayers are answered. Hence prayers to the non-living such as the sun, fire, and to humans whether they be Jesus, Moses or even Muhammad are rejected, as Allah informs us in the opening chapter of the Qur'an, known as Soorah Al-Faatihah, verse 4:¬†  "You alone do we worship and from you alone do we seek help."  A Muslim believes that Allah and His creation are distinctly different¬† entities. Neither is Allah His creation or a part of it, nor is His creation Him or a part of Him. Ultimately, it is the belief that the essence of Allah is everywhere in His creation or that His divine being is or was present in some aspects of His creation, which has provided justification for the worship of creation. Islam, hence, is a clear call to the worship of the Creator and the rejection of creation-worship in any form.¬†    THE MIRACLE OF QUR'AN    "And if you are in doubt as to what We [Allah] have revealed‚Ä¶then produce a Soorah (chapter) like thereunto"(Soorah Baqarah 2:23) This was the challenge put forth by Allah in the Qur'an 1400 years ago. As of yet, none has or will ever come close to meeting this challenge. Hence, as a result, multitudes throughout the centuries have believed and continue to believe in the Qur'an as a revelation beyond any human capacity. Modern scientists, for instance, have been amazed by the accuracy of scientific information presented in the Qur'an. Here are just a few examples:¬†  In his book of embryology-'The Developing Human' [W.B. Saunders Publishing, 1982], Dr. Keith Moore added a whole chapter to discuss the scientific accuracy of the Quranic discussion of this science. Another eminent scientist, Dr. Maurice Bucaille wrote in his book-'The Bible, the Qur'an and Science':¬†  "I could not find a single error in the Qur'an‚Ä¶if a man was the author of the Qur'an how could he have written facts in the 7th century A.D. that today are shown to be in keeping with modern scientific knowledge" Facts about astronomy, the animal world and other natural phenomenon, that were alien to modern science not long ago, are scattered among the messages of Allah's Unity and His Attributes throughout the miracle that is known as al-Qur'an .

(Tarantino later worked at another of the chain) 7. app. 00:44 -- the Playboy Club in West Hollywood, maybe, 8.  app. 00:46 -- the Manson girls, 9. app.00:48 -- Bruce Lee, 10. app.  01: 02 -- the Spahn Ranch, maybe, 11. app. 01:05 -- tv show HULLABALLOO, 12. app. 01:08 -- Charles Manson. text: Saw the movie a few days ago. I thought it was kinda boring and slow. There were some funny moments, lines, the Bruce Lee scene was awesome. The way the movie was shot was pretty cool. Tarantino gave it a great late sixties vibe with the cars and clothing worn by the cast. Great cast, obviously. Yet Al Pacino was in it for about 6 minutes. Very limited cameo by Luke Perry and the Charlie Manson character was just a blip of screen time. I think I was expecting more of the alternate universe Manson family story, instead of basically in the end of the movie. I've either really liked or loved every Tarantino movie or script he's been involved with that I've seen over the years. Maybe I'll like it a lot more the 2nd time around. I didn't like Jackie Brown the 1st time I saw it, but I love that movie now.

text: This is Tarantino's 'Godfather'. Every great director has their signature movie, their best work. This is his. What a incredible journey this movie is. Completely brilliant!! And an ending we can rejoice in.... knowing the reality we've lived with for 50 years. A masterpiece in filmmaking....

text: Loved the film & the creativity but it desperately needed a little editing & a few wardrobe choices.   Leonardo, over & over forgetting his non-sensical lines with no background bar patron chatter or atmosphere, like have the bar owners daughter actually come down & play the dam fiddle, anything to make it a little more interesting as this scene dragged on forever !  Why were we first to leave the Playboy mansion just as it was getting fun ?   Following Margo, wondering around aimlessly, like she was lost, in knee high white boots & a black long sleeve sweater, while on the strip, mid-day, bright sunshine summer hot, no wonder she lost the boots once inside the theatre.   Leonardo sweating profusely through out his cowboy scenes in his winter apparel, dyed Custer leather jacket & this heavy purple corduroy pull over sweat-shirt, like the wardrobe lady was playing a joke on him.   Why all the bravado about how we turned the strip into 1969,  L.A with no CGI., then suddenly mix in all this CGI vintage action film footage in Italy or when Leonardo played Steve McQueen, not even remotely realistic looking, in the Great Escape & finally streamline, lengthen the fantastic song choices are just a few obvious suggestions.    Quentin edited 4 hours of film down to 2 hours & 40 minutes, one only wonders what was left on the cutting room floor as Margo never got in the pool at the mansion per the trailer?   Simply not as polished as the movie trailer which was a fantastic, beautifully orchestrated mix of cinematography & song, but still overall an absolutely awesome movie !  I would love to see the 4 hour version with extended musical scenes !!
author: Major Tom
